%%TITLE
Contribution of human papilloma virus to the incidence of squamous cell carcinoma of the head and neck in a European population with high smoking prevalence.
%%ABSTRACT
Increases in incidence of oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OPSCC) in countries with falling tobacco use have been attributed to a growing role of human papilloma virus (HPV) in the carcinogenesis. Trends of HPV prevalence in populations with persistently high portions of smokers are poorly characterised.Registry data from East Germany were used to determine incidence trends between 1998 and 2011. Data from patients treated at the CharitÃ© University Medicine Berlin between 2004 and 2013 (cohort 1, N=436) were used for estimation of trends in HPV prevalence, smoking and survival. HPV prevalence was prospectively confirmed in cohort 2 (N=213) comprising all primary HNSCC cases at the CharitÃ© in 2013.Between 1998 and 2011 incidence of both OPSCC and non-OPSCC increased. An increase in HPV prevalence (% of HPV+ cases in 2004-2006 versus 2012-2013: 27% versus 59%, P=0.0004) accompanied by a moderate decrease in the portion of current smokers was observed in OPSCC but not in non-OPSCC. The change in disease epidemiology in OPSCC was associated with significant improvement in overall survival. Increased HPV prevalence in OPSCC (48%) compared to non-OPSCC (11%) was confirmed in cohort 2.Despite clear differences to the United States in terms of tobacco use, the increase in OPSCC incidence in a European population was also mainly attributed to HPV, and the HPV status significantly affected prognosis. For clinical trial design it is important to consider the large group of smokers within HPV-induced OPSCC.
%%METHODS
Data sources
We used data from the Common Tumor Registry of the federal states of Berlin, Brandenburg, Mecklenburg- Western Pomerania, Saxony-Anhalt, Saxony and Thurin- gia (1998–2011). Only cases with squamous cell histology were included. Subsite coding was according to the ICD-O-3 classiﬁcation, and subsite grouping was done in accordance with Braakhuis et al. (for more detail see available online).
Patient characteristics
Two patient cohorts were included for assessment of HPV prevalence trends. Cohort 1 consisted of patients who had been treated at the Charite´ Radi- ooncology and Radiotherapy department within the last 10 years, consented to participate in studies for the evaluation of prognostic/predictive biomarkers for treatment outcome (EA4/090/08; EA2/086/10) and from whom the HPV status of the primary tumour tissue had been determined as part of the bio- marker programme. Cohort 2 consisted of all consec- utive cases who presented between January 2013 and

Assessment of HPV status
HPV status was determined using a two-step algo- rithm: ﬁrst, p16Ink4 protein expression as surrogate marker for HPV was assessed by immunohistochemistry in all cases. Tumour samples showing strong, diﬀuse cytoplasmic and nuclear staining of p16 in >10% of car-
cinoma cells were subjected to Luminex®-based mul-
tiplexed genotyping for detection of HPV-speciﬁc DNA. Only cases positive for both p16 (deﬁned by strong nuclear staining in >70% cells) and HPV DNA were considered to be ‘true HPV-positive’. Details on p16 immunohistochemistry and HPV DNA genotyping are provided as online.
Statistical analysis
Average annual percent changes in European age- standardised rates per 100,000 inhabitants (ESR) were calculated and signiﬁcant changes in trends were determined using the jointpoint regression programme (version 4.1.1) provided as free download at the home- page of the Surveillance, Epidemiology and End Results Program. Overall and progression-free survival was compared by using Kaplan–Meier analysis and the log-rank test. Interactions between time of ﬁrst diagno- sis, clinical parameters and overall survival were evaluated using the Cox regression model. Statistical analyses were carried out using the SPSS Statistics software (version 22.0.0, IBM, Armonk, NY, USA). The level of signiﬁcance was set at P < 0.05.
Results
Incidence trends for HNSCC between 1998 and 2011
During the observation period of 14 years increasing trends in the incidence were observed for both genders in all main HNSCC sites (). The increase in incidence was more pronounced for carcinomas of the oral cavity and oropharynx compared to the two other subsites. Interestingly, an apparent change in carcinoma rates of the oral cavity and the oropharynx was recorded exclusively for males: While incidences were increasing in the period of 1998–2007, a plateau phase was reached with no signiﬁcant changes thereafter ().
Prevalence trends of HPV-associated HNSCC: a retrospective cohort analysis
In total, 118 of 436 carcinomas (27%) in cohort 1 were HPV-positive. As expected, HPV prevalence was signiﬁcantly higher in OPSCC compared to non-OPSCC (% HPV+ cases: OPSCC, 40%; non-OPSCC: 13%;
P < 0.0001). Overall, 286 of 436 patients (66%) were cur-
rent smokers. HPV prevalence was higher in the group of never/ex-smokers compared to current smokers (% HPV+ cases: never/ex-smokers, 37%; current smokers: 22%; P = 0.001). No diﬀerence in the age at ﬁrst diagno- sis was observed between HPV+ and HPV cases (mean years ± standard deviation: HPV cases, 58 ± 9; HPV+ cases: 60 ± 9; P = 0.21).
For time trend analysis patients were stratiﬁed into
four calendar period groups using the time of ﬁrst diagnosis as stratiﬁcation parameter. HPV prevalence signiﬁcantly increased across calendar periods in OPS- CC (A). Interestingly, the increase in the relative number of HPV+ cases among OPSCC did not start before 2010 but HPV prevalence nonetheless increased

Although the increase in HPV prev- alence was paralleled by a decrease in the portion of current smokers among OPSCC patients the change in the smoking habits was less pronounced, with a reduction of only 22% during the same period of time. In non-OPSCC, no signiﬁcant change in HPV prevalence was observed and the portion of current smokers even increased per trend over time in this group of patients (B).
Prevalence trends of HPV-associated HNSCC: a prospective survey analysis
Since cohort 1 represented a collection of patients participating in biomarker studies a selection bias with impact on HPV prevalence trends cannot be excluded. Patient outcome is aﬀected by the epidemiologic shift in OPSCC but not non-OPSCC
Several studies have previously demonstrated supe- rior outcome of HPV+ compared to HPV- OPSCC
patients. This was irrespective of the type of treatment tested in these studies, being either radiation , chemo- radiation , cetuximab-based bioradiation or che- motherapy in the neoadjuvant or palliative setting . We tested whether the increasing trends in HPV prevalence observed in cohort 1 were also associated with improved outcome. As shown in , we observed signiﬁcantly improved overall survival (OS) and a trend towards better PFS in OPSCC patients with diagnosis and treatment between 2010 and 2013 compared to patients diagnosed before 2010. The 2-year OS rates ±95% conﬁdence intervals were 71%

This signiﬁ- cant diﬀerence in OS between the two OPSCC groups was still observed after correction for Union for Interna- tional Cancer Control (UICC) stage and type of treat- ment (radiation versus chemoradiation) in multivariate analysis (). No improvement of OS or PFS was observed for the group of non-OPSCC patients (, right panel).
Smoking habits remain an independent risk of death in HPV+ OPSCC
Smoking has previously been identiﬁed as indepen- dent risk factor for tumour recurrence and death also in patients with HPV-driven carcinomas . Since we observed a persistently high prevalence of current smokers in OPSCC even in patients with an HPV+ car- cinoma (), we evaluated whether outcome is com- promised by smoking habits in patients with HPV+ tumours. While only one death was observed in the group of patients who never smoked or quit smoking at least one year before ﬁrst diagnosis (N = 50), 10
patients from the group of current smokers (N = 41)
died from their disease ().
